## 2. NO₂ Data (CAMS Air Quality)

### Training NO₂ — `fetch.py`

| Item | Source | Tag | Detail |
|------|--------|-----|--------|
| Raw hourly NO₂ | 🟢 Open-Meteo CAMS Air Quality API | **LIVE** | Real CAMS reanalysis data |
| Daily aggregation | 🟢 Computed from real hourly data | **LIVE** | `groupby("date").mean()` |
| **Scale correction** | 🔵 Multiplied by **×7–12×** | **REAL + SCALED** | Raw CAMS median ≈ 3–5 μg/m³ for this region. Code detects `median < 5.0` and multiplies by `NO2_BASELINE[city]["default"] / median`. This pushes Monastir to ~34 μg/m³ and Mahdia to ~28 μg/m³. |

> [!WARNING]
> **The scale correction is the biggest "stretch" in the project.** The raw CAMS data is real, but the 7-12× multiplier is based on `NO2_BASELINE` values from `cities.py` which are **manually set from literature estimates** (`monastir: 34.0, mahdia: 28.0`). These literature baselines are reasonable for the Sahel industrial corridor but are NOT from ground-truth sensors.

### Runtime NO₂ — `predict.py → _fetch_current_no2()`

| Item | Source | Tag |
|------|--------|-----|
| Last 10 days hourly NO₂ | 🟢 Open-Meteo CAMS (live) | **LIVE** |
| Daily aggregation | 🟢 Computed from API data | **LIVE** |
| Scale correction | 🔵 Same ×7-12× multiplier applied | **REAL + SCALED** |

---

## 3. Model Predictions

| Item | Source | Tag | Detail |
|------|--------|-----|--------|
| XGBoost model | 🟢 Trained on real (scaled) data | **LIVE** | Trained on 1927 days of ERA5+CAMS |
| `no2_mean_pred` (single point) | 🟢 Model inference on live weather + NO₂ | **LIVE** | Real prediction from trained model |
| **Grid cell spatial variation** | 🟡 `rng.normal(0, 2.5)` jitter | **SYNTHETIC JITTER** | The model produces ONE prediction per city. Each grid cell gets `no2_pred + random_jitter(σ=2.5)`. The spatial pattern is **fake** — there is no real spatial resolution. |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The heatmap spatial variation is synthetic.** The model predicts a single NO₂ value for the whole city. The per-cell differences on the map are random Gaussian noise (σ=2.5 μg/m³) with a fixed seed. The "hot spots" you see are from the random number generator, NOT from real spatial data.

